   <text type="letter">
      <body>
         <pb facs="facs/johnson01.jpg" xml:id="pb0001" n="1"/>
         <head type="metadata">
             <name corresp="#RUJ">Robert Underwood Johnson</name> to <addressee>
               <name corresp="#SLC">Samuel L. Clemens</name>
            </addressee>
             <date when="1884-03-31">31 March 1884</date> &#x2022; <name type="place">New York, New York</name>
            <sourceline>(MS, postal card: CSmH, UCLC 41957)</sourceline>
         </head>
         <div1 type="letter" xml:id="lt0001">
            <opener>
               <dateline>
                  <date when="1884-03-31"><hi rend="italic">March 31.</hi>
                  </date> <space extent="20"/>33 E. 17<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> St, N.Y. City<lb/>
                  <space extent="26"/><hi rend="italic">Century Magazine</hi>
               </dateline>
                    <note type="ed" place="inline" xml:id="ed001">written vertically in the left margin:</note>
                    <hi rend="italic">Confidential</hi>
               <salute>M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> S. L. Clemens,</salute>
               <salute>Dear Sir:</salute>
            </opener>

            <p>Could you let me have an autograph of yours for a lame boy whose mother has interested him in things spiritual by encouraging him to make an autograph collection to be raffled for at a fair, the proceeds to go to the Society for the Suppression of the Toy Pistol. I dislike to ask you point blank and so merely suggest the evident propriety of aiding this good work.</p>
            <closer>
               <salute rend="indentcompclose">Yours very truly</salute>
               <signed rend="indentsig">R. U. Johnson</signed>
            </closer>
         </div1>
